Update rotatedRectangleIntersection function to calculate near to origin

* Change type used in points function from RotatedRect

In the function that sets the points of a RotatedRect, the types

should be double in order to keep the precision when dealing with
RotatedRects that are defined far from the origin.

This commit solves the problem in some assertions from
rotatedRectangleIntersection when dealing with rectangles far from
origin.

* added proper type casts

* Update rotatedRectangleIntersection function to calculate near to origin

This commit changes the rotatedRectangleIntersection function in order
to calculate the intersection of two rectangles considering that they
are shifted near the coordinates origin (0, 0).

This commit solves the problem in some assertions from
rotatedRectangleIntersection when dealing with rectangles far from
origin.

* Revert type changes in types.cpp and adequate code to c++98

* Revert unnecessary casts on types.cpp

Change-Id: Ia4c33f76e987333542deab01bf23f203ac379887","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/eeaf1597c43d1913d0127566064209d7ad4359b5"},{"sha":"4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470","author":{"name":"Jacques Pienaar","email":"8b5f536c3e2f2b8ae266b27bc9085a584b5bd904@google.com"},"message":"Extract inliner policy into helper function and apply policy in TF dialect

Enable using multi device body inliner policy in TF dialect inliner. This is a rather minimal change while duplicating to avoid heavier dependencies before refactoring. Currently in the dialect only explicit multi device placement is handled and the previous behavior is retained for the rest for now.

This may also get revised as the behavior when inlined or not inlined is not uniform.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380391172
Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

[{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

Corzine","email":"666f57d501df97ea05feb3144199cddcc0d4dc58@ties.org"},"message":"Implement support for TIMING-MARK option.

Attempt to use the TELNET protocol TIMING-MARK option (RFC 860) to
implement end-to-end acknowledgements, if possible.  Supporting TELNET
implementations must respond to IAC DO TIMING-MARK with an appropriate
response of IAC WILL TIMING-MARK or IAC WON'T TIMING-MARK, depending on
whether or not the implementation is providing assurance that all output
before the IAC DO TIMING-MARK has been "completely processed, printed,
discarded, or otherwise disposed of."

Unlike normal TELNET options, this particular option is stateless, and
supporting implementations are required to respond to EACH request with
an appropriate response.  Furthermore, conforming TELNET implementations
which do NOT understand this option are ALSO required to respond to each
request (with IAC WON'T TIMING-MARK), since this is a requirement of the
base TELNET protocol for unrecognized options.  As such, any conforming
TELNET client should respond, whether or not it understands the option.

Of course, in the real world, a client may not correctly implement the
TELNET protocol, or a user might be connecting with a simple TCP client
that doesn't support the TELNET protocol at all.  Therefore, attempt to
use the IAC DO TIMING-MARK sequence and remember whether or not the
client responded to it, before relying on this mechanism for end-to-end
acknowledgements.

If this mechanism appears to be unusable, disable the use of this option
and simulate an "acknowledgement" immediately after the preceding output
has been fully buffered by the kernel.  This doesn't provide end-to-end
confirmation that the output has been received by the client, but it
will have to do for any clients which don't respond to the option.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/deven/phoenix/commits/caf5707d27624eddbfdcece29ab54cc85bbed3c7"},{"sha":"8489f57658978da1fbecaf93385f2407d3577343","author":{"name":"Deven T. Enable using multi device body inliner policy in TF dialect inliner. This is a rather minimal change while duplicating to avoid heavier dependencies before refactoring. Currently in the dialect only explicit multi device placement is handled and the previous behavior is retained for the rest for now.

This may also get revised as the behavior when inlined or not inlined is not uniform.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380391172
Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sakib-rahman-bangladesh/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

[{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380398713

Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

* [Offscreen] Mount/unmount layout effects

Exposes the Offscreen component type and implements basic support for
mount/unmounting layout effects when the visibility is toggled.

Mostly it works the same way as hidden Suspense trees, which use the
same internal fiber type. I had to add an extra bailout, though, that
doesn't apply to the Suspense case but does apply to Offscreen
components: a hidden Offscreen tree will eventually render at low
priority, and when we it does, its `subtreeTag` will have effects
scheduled on it. So I added a check to the layout phase where, if the
subtree is hidden, we skip over the subtree entirely. An alternate
design would be to clear the subtree flags in the render phase, but I
prefer doing it this way since it's harder to mess up.

We also need an API to enable the same thing for passive effects. This
is not yet implemented.

* Add test starting from hidden

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380391172
Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

[{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

Tang","email":"765086fe2e0c1f980161f127fec596800f327f62@outlook.com"},"message":"Wire up set_filesystem_configuration with modular file system

This PR tries to wire up set_filesystem_configuration with
modular file system so that it is possible to set up the file
system configuration through modular file system plugins.

While set_filesystem_configuration API has been defined in
the past, the API was not wired up with modular file system
so it was not possible to use it from plugins.

This PR adds the missing implementation.

This PR also made several changes:
- values associated with `type_tag` was not defined in the past. This
  PR adds the definition.
- TF_Filesystem_Option_Value definition has been modified as previous
  unnamed union was difficult to assign value.
- set_filesystem_configuration_option was removed as it is almost
  a duplicate of set_filesystem_configuration, and it does not
  match the description.

While the API was modified, since set_filesystem_configuration
was not wired with modular file system, it is not used anyway.
So this will not break user or plugins.

* Wire up DOM legacy build

* Hack to filter extra comments for testing purposes

* Use string concat in renderToString

I think this might be faster. We could probably use a combination of this
technique in the stream too to lower the overhead.

* Error if we can't complete the root synchronously

Maybe this should always error but in the async forms we can just delay
the stream until it resolves so it does have some useful semantics.

In the synchronous form it's never useful though. I'm mostly adding the
error because we're testing this behavior for renderToString specifically.

* Gate memory leak tests of internals

These tests don't translate as is to the new implementation and have been
ported to the Fizz tests separately.

* Enable Fizz legacy mode in stable

* Add wrapper around the ServerFormatConfig for legacy mode

This ensures that we can inject custom overrides without negatively
affecting the new implementation.

This adds another field for static mark up for example.

* Wrap pushTextInstance to avoid emitting comments for text in static markup

* Don't emit static mark up for completed suspense boundaries

Completed and client rendered boundaries are only marked for the client
to take over.

Pending boundaries are still supported in case you stream non-hydratable
mark up.

* Wire up generateStaticMarkup to static API entry points

* Mark as renderer for stable

This shouldn't affect the FB one ideally but it's done with the same build
so let's hope this works.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelseblani/react/commits/dbe3363ccd125f89c25fea234031410408f0df09"},{"sha":"a8f5e77b921c890c215fb1c7e24a06f38598deb1","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove invokeGuardedCallback from commit phase (#21666)

(#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't

[{"sha":"4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470","author":{"name":"Jacques Pienaar","email":"8b5f536c3e2f2b8ae266b27bc9085a584b5bd904@google.com"},"message":"Extract inliner policy into helper function and apply policy in TF dialect

Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

This commit adds six new commands to interact with system clipboard:
- clipboard-yank
- clipboard-yank-join
- clipboard-paste-after
- clipboard-paste-before
- clipboard-paste-replace
- show-clipboard-provider

System clipboard provider is detected by checking a few environment
variables and executables. Currently only built-in detection is
supported.

`clipboard-yank` will only yank the "main" selection, which is currently the first
one. This will need to be revisited later.

mappable.

Change-Id: I8ca07f9c470fa7331766e4a1e3f80a02ad87414d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/b26d22636d21dc07a697d062b27f371040d47678"},{"sha":"2692a305ad9a4013b28572084ad81cd2b1646fbc","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[NFC] [GPU] Introduce a unified class for CudaComputeCapability and use it

We've never introduced a proper class for CudaComputeCapability since it's just
a pair of ints, and as a result almost every second client ended up
reimplementing it.

Introduce a new unified class and properly use it.

Rationale for no error handling: compute capability of "0" usually already
represents the intent, and the current error handling was widely inconsistent
across the codebase.
Almost all the users just want to check whether compute capability is greater
than X and do not care about error conditions.

Removes ~200LOC

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380391172
Change-Id: Iaeac7568c573d9d900c3b0b32fad79f7b2b8efe3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/4353153bc128e1986ae0e7c2f1880d99827af470"},{"sha":"67a33c36c280e45cb034342b7d41f3287e715d98","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"Refactor collective tests

Collective tests contain large chunks of repeated code. It makes the tests difficult to read. Adding a collective implementation results in people copy-pasting large chunks of code as well (permuter_test, added recently).

This change:
1. Move common utils to a separate file.
2. Remove the logic to calculate subdivisions from tests. Those are duplicates to InitializeCollectiveParams().
3. Stop providing collective kernel in CollectiveContext for tests. It's only used in very limited places. It's not ideal to have collectives depend on OpKernel since it's a complicated interface. It's only used to invoke merge_op and final_op for CollectiveReduce. We can further remove it by changing merge_op and final_op to merge_func and final_func, but this change is already large enough so I'll leave it later.
4. Use virtual GPUs instead of using the same GPUs for different ranks. The latter breaks the invariant of some collective implementation.

Tang","email":"765086fe2e0c1f980161f127fec596800f327f62@outlook.com"},"message":"Wire up set_filesystem_configuration with modular file system

This PR tries to wire up set_filesystem_configuration with
modular file system so that it is possible to set up the file
system configuration through modular file system plugins.

While set_filesystem_configuration API has been defined in
the past, the API was not wired up with modular file system
so it was not possible to use it from plugins.

This PR adds the missing implementation.

This PR also made several changes:
- values associated with `type_tag` was not defined in the past. This
  PR adds the definition.
- TF_Filesystem_Option_Value definition has been modified as previous
  unnamed union was difficult to assign value.
- set_filesystem_configuration_option was removed as it is almost
  a duplicate of set_filesystem_configuration, and it does not
  match the description.

While the API was modified, since set_filesystem_configuration
was not wired with modular file system, it is not used anyway.
So this will not break user or plugins.

Previously, DevTools recursed over both children and siblings during mount. This caused potential stack overflows when there were a lot of children (e.g. a list containing many items).

Given the following example component tree:

       A
    B  C  D
    E     F
          G

A method that recurses for every child and sibling leads to a max depth of 6:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> B -> C
    A -> B -> C -> D
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets either deeper or wider.

A method that recurses for every child and iterates over siblings leads to a max depth of 4:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> C
    A -> D
    A -> D -> F
    A -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets deeper but is resilient to wide trees (e.g. lists containing many items).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/amitkumar98/react/commits/a0d6b155dc3a182162b9f91baac33df39d7919df"},{"sha":"7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Removed (deleted) tracing fixture test from relesae scripts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/amitkumar98/react/commits/7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004"},{"sha":"2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Preparing DevTools 4.12.4 -> 4.13.0 release (#21378)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/amitkumar98/react/commits/2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37"},{"sha":"207d4c3a535d4624f17634baa6bfe613f5f3e4e6","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Revert "Support nesting of startTransition and flushSync (alt) (#21149)"

This reverts commit 2e7aceeb5c8b6e5c61174c0e9731e263e956e445.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all
passive effects from being treated this way.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/amitkumar98/react/commits/7bac7607a764074e66dd57c68c09ec5cc898f4a5"}]

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PrinceRajRoy/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PrinceRajRoy/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

1, add hlo-to-lhlo support for DynamicReshape and DynamicBroadcastInDim

2, add a flag `convert-to-lmhlo-only` to seperate following two case:
   - hlo-to-lhlo only. Simply lowers all mhlo ops to their lmhlo
     counterparts, do not apply any optimization (e.g. elide any
     buffer copy). Buffer optimization is not easy in dynamic
     shape world especially when involving control flow, thus we
     leave this to another dedicated pass.

This commit adds six new commands to interact with system clipboard:
- clipboard-yank
- clipboard-yank-join
- clipboard-paste-after
- clipboard-paste-before
- clipboard-paste-replace
- show-clipboard-provider

System clipboard provider is detected by checking a few environment
variables and executables. Currently only built-in detection is
supported.

`clipboard-yank` will only yank the "main" selection, which is currently the first
one. This will need to be revisited later.

Closes https://github.com/helix-editor/helix/issues/76","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pickfire/helix/commits/a2b8cfca34433b1d4595143652e10b58685d0dc0"},{"sha":"f50261c944d8cfbb5775dc9350f64a6eefde0295","author":{"name":"Benoît CORTIER","email":"47bf50382743ae82b15257aa91b80293303837cc@fried-world.eu"},"message":"Add mappable commands for system clipboard

System clipboard integration exists now in two favors: typable and
mappable.

Default mappings are:
- SPC p: paste clipboard after
- SPC P: paste clipboard before
